data.text:
This weekend, captain Thomas Harbo Jakobsen with crew flew our very first flight to the brand new Berlin Brandenburg Airport.  Upon arrival, Berlin was bathed in the beautiful fall sunlight, giving our aircraft the best welcoming possible💙

#flysas #helloBER https://t.co/Ttqhkrt1GM

Prime time has come for the northern lights, and travelers long for the north to get a glimpse of the vivid colors dancing across the night sky. 
Pilot Thomas Hjelset had the luxury of being seated front row for this magical light show during the approach to Bardufoss🌌 #flysas https://t.co/aypNMJV5lD

The Svalbard archipelago, situated between mainland Norway and the North Pole, offer magical sunsets as the polar night approaches. It is the time of year when the sun doesn’t rise above the horizon and days are pitch black – unless the northern light enchants the sky💙 #flysas https://t.co/cMNHp1g5X2

The deicing of SK4417, captured by Air Hostess Ragnhild Mofoss, in front of the scenic and snowy Tromsø peaks. Safety is our highest priority, and deicing prevents ice buildup on the aircraft - keeping it safe during the cold months up North ❄️ #flysas #norway #tromsø https://t.co/oEItGrhNZs

data.text: Flying into the Danish capital, we can just about feel the fall breeze over the Sound separating Denmark from the Swedish mainland. This windy shot have us longing for walks along the coastline of Sjælland. We’ll get you there safely 🇩🇰 #flysas #wearetravelers #denmark https://t.co/dAW2a5EgHq

Today we use a Ted Bernhardtz standard updated blue uniform in combination with SAS blue items, scarf, tie and ladies’ top.​The pattern of the silk scarf is inspired by the Nordic landscape seen from above💙 #flysas #Travelersmakehistory https://t.co/HTHnFynknY

Last year, we proudly introduced our current aircraft design. Our aircraft now carry the iconic blue color both on the tail, the engines and the wingtips. The word “Scandinavian”, has been placed on the belly of the plane✈️💙 #flysas #wearetravelers #travelersmakehistory https://t.co/UU0golBGYN
Our prospectus has now been published. Find it here:  ✈️ #flysas $SAS https://t.co/oySgLvUxWM

To get you safely where you need to go, we have implemented a few measures. But we need your help as well! Here are some of the measures we’ve taken, and what you can do to stay healthy while traveling. 💙 #flysas #SASSafeTravel https://t.co/JyEWbInFKL

From 29 September, we are glad to be reopening the route from Copenhagen to Shanghai with a weekly frequency, operated by our brand new Airbus A350 - one of the most modern and fuel-efficient in the industry, emitting up to 30% less than previous comparable aircraft.✈️ #flysas https://t.co/0U0QooxfvO

Whatever your reason for traveling, and whenever the season, we take you safely and smoothly to where you need to go. All travelers get double the EuroBonus points when booking a trip departing up until May 31st 2021. Book before October 21st 2020 💙#flysas #saseurobonus https://t.co/qfQZUMU3Vj

A blue tail, red engines and a redesigned logo were elements of the new look introduced in 1998. The flags of the Scandinavian countries were now removed from the aircraft body and instead displayed over one of the cabin windows✈️ #flysas #travelersmakehistory⠀ https://t.co/BW15hVForB

data.text:
After more than 30 years with our ergonomic and sustainable design, the famous SAS coffee pot is still used by 35 airlines and it is featured in the permanent collection of the MoMA Museum of Modern Art☕

#flysas #travelersmakehistory https://t.co/LEz4JzLx69

Flight Captain Espen with crew Jan and Lars ready to take this new Airbus A320neo from Oslo to Tromsø up north. With up to 18% less CO2 emissions and 30% less noise than its predecessor, this aircraft marks an important step on the road to sustainable aviation✈️ #flysas https://t.co/nyi4VpNrno

A magical moment up in the air captured by colleague Tina. After 39 years at SAS, she knows we will always keep flying – and how to get the best out of the window seat✈️ #flysas https://t.co/NdVefzgkTY

The “Scandinavian belly stripes” livery design, with a white fuselage, was created in 1983 - reflecting the aspects of the Danish, Norwegian and Swedish flags
 ✈️ #flysas https://t.co/PreZgRLl4B

At Stegastein lookout, a little less than 3 hours from Bergen, Norwegian home-explorers find one of the most ravishing views of Vestlandet. We’ll get you there safely 💙 #flysas ⠀ https://t.co/uPr8e5tY36

The first SAS aircraft livery design anno 1946 centered around a symbol common to all three Scandinavian countries: The dragon headed viking longship✈️ #flysas #travelersmakehistory https://t.co/LCconAorTx

Taking it back to the late nineties – Modern flexibility in focus ✈️ The 1999 SAS Uniform design team created a flexible uniform wardrobe with a lot of items to choose from. #flysas https://t.co/yg5Z3rSWaf
